dar transmitter and receiver in the missile, making it unnecessary for the pilot to keep the aircraft aimed at the target after firing the missile, unlike Semi-active radar homing (SARH) missiles which require continuous radar-assisted guidance throughout flight. This allowed the aircraft that fired the AAM-N-3 to turn away, prosecute other targets, and/or escape from potential retaliatory missiles fired by the enemy aircraft during the time it takes for the Sparrow to reach its target. Despite the significant advantages of this design over SARH guidance, all subsequent models of the Sparrow use semi-active radar homing.", "qas": [{"question": "what was unique about the aam-n-3 bird ?", "answers": [], "id": "(3, 24, 0)"}, {"question": "what kind of radar did the sparrow use ?", "answers": [], "id": "(3, 24, 3)"}]}, {"context": "To accommodate the active radar guidance system, the AAM-N-3 Sparrow II had a much greater volume than its predecessor. Its size would subsequently set the precedent for all future Sparrow variants.", "qas": [{"question": "what type of bird had a better volume ?", "answers": [], "id": "(3, 25, 0)"}, {"question": "what was the size of all new lyric variants ?", "answers": [], "id": "(3, 25, 1)"}]}, {"context": "In 1959, Canadair had completed five missiles based on airframes from Douglas, and built two models from scratch, when the program was cancelled with the cancellation of the Arrow.", "qas": []}, {"context": "Skyguard I is an anti-aircraft system, utilizing ground-based AIM-7 Sparrow launchers.", "qas": [{"question": "what type of system is skyguard i ?", "answers": [], "id": "(3, 27, 0)"}]}, {"context": "The Italian company Finmeccanica (now Leonardo S.p.A.), Alenia Difesa licensed the AIM-7E Sparrow technology from the US, and produced its own improved version called Aspide.", "qas": []}, {"context": "The LY-60/FD-60/PL-10 is a family of PRC missiles developed by the Shanghai Academy of Science and Technology, largely based on the Ital